   "source": [
    "# **Inversion Scheme**\n",
    "\n",
    "Genetic programming is a special field of evolutionary computation that aims at building programs automatically to solve problems independently of their domain. The algorithm does not know the details of the problem it is trying to solve. The problem of deciding how much better a particular model is requires a little more thought. As it progresses, the genetic algorithm is designed to retain the better models preferentially through stochastic sampling processes so that the fitter models are more likely to survive and procreate. In effect, that probability of a given model being sampled and selected for the next stage of the genetic algorithm depends on its fitness value (Gallagher & Sambridge, 1994).\n",
    "\n",
    "In the inversion, we chose the P-wave velocity perturbations as the parameters to be determined, because they significantly affect the sound speed of water column. In the\n",
    "GA, these parameters are encoded in gene type that is suitable for the genetic operations. Variants are possible at most stages of the genetic algorithm, although the basic requirements always include the encoding, evaluation, and operation stages (Gallagher & Sambridge, 1994).\n",
    "\n",
    "![image.png](attachment:5dec6687-ba36-4ba2-bdc2-f10371783cf6.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "Flowdiagram of the modified GA-based inversion method by Yamanaka and H. Ishida (1996).\n",
    "\n",
    "## **In the inversion, we searched at each layer for an optimal combination of:**\n",
<<<<<<< HEAD
    "- Sound speed.\n",
=======
    "- S-wave velocity,\n",
    "- Thickness.\n",
>>>>>>> 028cf37d1dc8a459a17f99af11a917a3fc5fb03d
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## **Building upon the previous figure, a detailed description of the functions used to generate the genetic algorithm is provided below:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Initialization**:  Randomly create models for the initial population within a given range of random layer thicknesses and shear-wave velocities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "47908ef0-0f67-4cf4-9490-9a229ad28880",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "2. **Evaluation**: After defining a population of models, we create a function to estimate the fitness value (misfit function) for each model;"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a8a61f02-ed52-47cf-8fb2-b67ee7c77634",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Misfit definition:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Given an individual (random model), the theoretical dispersion curve is computed, and the misfit value is evaluated. \n",
    "\n",
    "the misfit is defined as\n",
    "\n",
    "$misfit = \\sqrt{\\sum_{i=1}^{n^f}\\frac{(x_{di}-x_{ci})^2}{n_{f}}}$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $x_{di}$ is the velocity of the data curve at frequency $f_{i}$;\n",
    "- $x_{ci}$ is the velocity of the calculated curve at frequency $f_{i}$;\n",
    "- $n_{f}$ is the number of frequency samples considered."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a11e43c6-e8b9-4244-9c2c-0ad3b77e781f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "3. **Statistics**: Compute the mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of the individuals' fitness values to track the optimization progress;"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e5d2db46-dac3-4c85-854f-a9bd675cc39c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "4. **Selection**: Process of choosing individuals from the population to form the next generation. It is based on their fitness, with the goal of selecting individuals that will contribute the best genetic material to future generations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "889b0d02-52d4-4055-9b29-ffc6e790cca9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*Tournament selection* chooses individuals for the next generation using tournament selection, where three candidates compete, and the fittest is selected;"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a68fa1c9-5fa5-48f2-be2c-f5244eae6899",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "5. **Mutation**: Each mutation has its own characteristics and may be applied to different types of individuals;"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a8b50590-2ded-4665-a205-d56ab22167aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "6. **Crossover**: They only mate individuals, this means that an independent copies must be made prior to mating the individuals if the original individuals have to be kept or are references to other individuals;"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "71bbddb2-d69b-4fae-8353-14d4bd336eaf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "7. **Hall of fame**: Specific structure which contains the n best individuals."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "199ea3be-dc52-42dc-9102-9951f76d98c3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A special structure in DEAP that stores the n best individuals found during the evolutionary process. \n",
    "\n",
    "It preserves top-performing solutions, ensuring they are not lost due to genetic operations like crossover or mutation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9feb6bee-bbc2-45eb-a616-379dd2049071",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For a more detailed explanation of each step, please refer to https://deap.readthedocs.io/en/master/tutorials/basic/part1.html."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "77b11a8a-ccb5-44ba-8c07-51d9f7db171a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# **DEAP Configuration for Evolutionary Algorithm Setup**\n",
    "\n",
    "The toolbox is intended to contain all the evolutionary tools, from the object initializers to the evaluation operator.\n",
    "It allows easy configuration of each algorithm. \n",
    "\n",
    "This function configures the DEAP framework for a genetic algorithm, defining the necessary components for evolutionary processes such as initialization, evaluation, crossover, mutation, and selection. The configuration follows these steps:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Fitness and Individual Creation**:  \n",
    "   It creates a `FitnessMin` class for minimizing the fitness value and a custom `Individual` class that holds a list and is associated with the fitness class.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Toolbox Initialization**:  \n",
    "   The `Toolbox` object is instantiated to store and manage evolutionary operators. These operators are essential for the algorithm’s processes.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Attribute Generator**:  \n",
    "   The `model` function, based on a uniform distribution of layer thickness and shear-wave velocities, generates the individual attributes.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Individual and Population Initialization**:  \n",
    "   The toolbox registers functions to create an individual by applying the `model` generator and to initialize a population from repeated individual generations.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Evaluation Function**:  \n",
    "   The `evaluate` function computes the misfit value between the theoretical and true dispersion curves, using the `inversion_objective` function.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. **Crossover Operation**:  \n",
    "   A two-point crossover operation (`mate`) is registered, allowing the mixing of two individuals to exchange genetic information, ensuring diversity in the population.\n",
    "\n",
    "7. **Mutation Operation**:  \n",
    "    The `mutate_gaussian` function applies a mutation by adding Gaussian noise to the values of an individual's attributes. This introduces small random variations, facilitating the exploration of new solutions while maintaining the structure of the individual.\n",
    "\n",
    "8. **Selection Strategy**:  \n",
    "   A tournament selection method is used (`select`), where three individuals are randomly selected, and the one with the best fitness is chosen for reproduction."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8a7caae6-6b62-475c-a95b-1834967cc12c",
